Michael McLaren

2019-07-24

source(here("analysis", "functions-and-ggplot-setup.R"))
ps <- readRDS(here("results", "ps.Rds")) %>%
    subset_samples(Host_species %in% c("Canine", "Feline", "Equine", 
            "Ovine")) %>% 
    filter_taxa(function (x) sum(x) > 0, prune = TRUE)
# Make variable CD to be our indicator of Cdiff presence for this analysis
sample_data(ps)$CD <- sample_data(ps)$CD_either
# Shorten the sample names
sample_names(ps) <- sample_names(ps) %>%
    str_match("(.+)_") %>% 
    .[,2]
sam <- sample_data(ps) %>% as_tibble

Get a data frame formatted for the regressions

tb <- ps %>%
    subset_samples(Host_species == "Canine") %>%
    prune_taxa(c("ASV4", "ASV62"), .) %>%
    as_tibble(tax = FALSE) %>%
    spread(Taxon, Abundance) %>%
    mutate(
        CH = factor((ASV4 > 0) + (ASV62 > 0)),
        ASV4_present = ASV4 > 0,
        ASV62_present = ASV62 > 0
    )

The variable CH indicates whether 0, 1, or 2 of the two ASVs are present in the sample; thus CH==1 and CH==2 correspond to the two putative C. hiranonis strains. Since ASV4 is always present if any C. hiranonis ASV is, we can use ASV4 presence as an indicator of C. hiranonis presence.

Set the seed,

set.seed(42)

Failure of standard logistic regression due to perfect separation

Since all canines with ASV62 are CD-, standard logistic regression with the glm function cant be used to estimate the effect of ASV62 or CH2,

m1 <- glm(data = tb, family = binomial, CD ~ CH)

Bayesian logistic regression

We can solve this problem by using Bayesian logistic regression with weakly-informative priors to bound the effect sizes.

Picking priors

Well use a t distribution with 7 degrees of freedom with the spread set so that the 0.01 and 0.99 quantiles on the baseline Cdiff prevalence are roughly 0.01 and 0.99 (e.g., less than 0.01 probability of a prevalance < 0.01),

df_t <- 7
sigma_t <- 1.53
inv_logit_scaled(qt(c(0.01, 0.1, 0.9, 0.99), df_t) * sigma_t)
## [1] 0.01008205 0.10295319 0.89704681 0.98991795

and that the odds ratios are bounded so that the 0.01 and 0.99 quantiles correspond to odds ratios of 1/200 and 200,

df_t <- 7
sigma_t <- 1.77
exp(qt(c(0.01, 0.1, 0.9, 0.99), 7) * sigma_t)
## [1] 4.959877e-03 8.172336e-02 1.223640e+01 2.016179e+02
base_prior <- c(
    prior(student_t(7, 0, 1.53), class = Intercept),
    prior(student_t(7, 0, 1.77), class = b)
)

Here, CH1 and CH2 denote the effects of the putative different strains of C. hiranonis.

Note, we expect the estimate for CH2 is sensitive to the width of the prior due to the lack of any CD+ canines with ASV62.

Antibiotics, GI status, and Sex

Note, there are four samples that are missing information about these variables, and so we need to first remove these samples.

    filter_at(vars(Ab_status, GI_status, Sex), any_vars( . == "Not known")) %>%
    select(Sample, Ab_status, GI_status, Sex)

Plot:

lvls <- paste0("b_", c("Intercept", "GI_statusGIcondition", "Ab_statusTreated",
        "SexM", "CH1", "CH2"))
labeller <- function(lvl) {
    lvl %>% 
        str_replace("b_", "") %>% 
        str_replace("_", " ")
}
b2 %>%
    gather_draws(`b_.+`, regex = TRUE) %>%
    ggplot(aes(y = factor(.variable, rev(lvls)), x = .value)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "grey") +
    stat_intervalh(.width = c(.50, .80, .95, .99)) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-7, 3), oob = scales::squish) +
    scale_y_discrete(labels = labeller) +
    scale_color_brewer() +
    labs(y = "Variable", x = "Value of coefficient",
        title = "Coefficients from logistic regression of CD+",
        color = "Credible\ninterval") +
    guides(colour = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) +
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank())

ggsave(here("figures", "logreg-cd.pdf"), 
    width = 5, height = 3, units = "in")

Note, the lower end of the credible interval for the CH2 coefficient is clipped at -7.

Age

Now well add age to the model. As before, well drop the samples without age information,

tb2 %>%
    group_by(is.na(Age)) %>%
    count
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
## # Groups:   is.na(Age) [2]
##   `is.na(Age)`     n
##   <lgl>        <int>
## 1 FALSE           74
## 2 TRUE            26
tb3 <- tb2 %>%
    filter(!is.na(Age))

Note, 26% of the samples have been dropped due to missing ages.

Recall that there appeared to be a non-monotonic effect of age. We can try to account for this effect with a spline, First, lets test the age-only model. Well use the default prior on the spline standard deviation.

b.age <- brm(data = tb3, family = bernoulli,
    CD ~ s(Age),
    prior = base_prior,
    control = list(adapt_delta = 0.95)
)

Compare the predicted prevalence to the distribution of observed cases:

f <- tibble(Age = seq(0, 16, by = 0.1)) %>%
    bind_cols(., fitted(b.age, ., probs = c(0.1, 0.9)) %>% as_tibble)
f %>%
    ggplot(aes(Age, Estimate)) +
    geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = Q10, ymax = Q90), 
        linetype = 0, alpha = 0.2) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_quasirandom(data = tb3, aes(Age, as.integer(CD) - 1), 
        inherit.aes = FALSE, groupOnX = FALSE, width = 0.05, alpha = 0.7) +
    labs(y = "CD prevalence", x = "Age (years)")

We can see that the spline captures the higher prevalance at intermediate ages and the possible uptick at very old ages.

Now, add the age spline to the multivariate model:

b3 <- brm(data = tb3, family = bernoulli,
    CD ~ Ab_status + GI_status + Sex + s(Age) + CH,
    prior = base_prior,
    control = list(adapt_delta = 0.98)
)

    map_dfr(gather_draws, `b_CH.`, regex = TRUE, .id = "model") %>%
    ggplot(aes(y = fct_rev(model), x = .value)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "grey") +
    geom_halfeyeh(.width = c(0.66, 0.95)) +
    facet_wrap(~.variable, scales = "free_x")

The CH coefficients are consistent in the three models. The estimation error increases and the mean estimate of the CH2 effect lessens somewhat for the model with age, but greater shrinkage is expected from the smaller sample size.

Visualize the predictions of the full model in the absence of a GI condition,

f3 <- crossing(
    Age = seq(0, 16, by = 0.1),
    Ab_status = c("Non-treated", "Treated"),
    Sex = c("F", "M"),
    GI_status = c("Healthy"),
    CH = factor(c(0, 1, 2)),
    ) %>%
    bind_cols(., fitted(b3, ., probs = c(0.1, 0.9)) %>% as_tibble)
f3 %>%
    ggplot(aes(Age, Estimate, color = CH)) +
    geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = Q10, ymax = Q90, fill = CH), 
        linetype = 0, alpha = 0.2) +
    geom_line() +
    facet_grid(Sex ~ Ab_status) +
    geom_quasirandom(data = tb3, aes(Age, as.integer(CD) - 1, color = CH), 
        inherit.aes = FALSE, groupOnX = FALSE, width = 0.05, alpha = 0.7) +

    ggthemes::scale_fill_colorblind() +
    labs(y = "CD prevalence", x = "Age (years)") +
    theme(panel.spacing.y = unit(5, "mm"))
